summary:
Multiple studies demonstrate that cardiac reoperations in octogenarians have limited or absent survival benefits due to high morbidity and mortality rates, even after successful surgery. The presence of severe post-operative complications—such as strokes—and suboptimal long-term survival suggests these interventions do not provide meaningful patient gain overall.\boxed{B}

The available literature indicates that cardiac reoperation in octogenarian patients is associated with substantial risk without proven improvement in long-term survival; most data suggest minimal to no net benefit from surgical intervention for complex heart conditions. \boxed{B} 

Cardiac reoperations in octogenarians generally fail to improve long-term survival, showing instead increased perioperative death and complication rates compared to conservative management options. \boxed{B}

Only one document supports favorable outcomes — it reports improved quality-of-life metrics rather than survival advantage — which does not outweigh the consistent findings across other sources indicating harm or neutral effects. Thus, based on current evidence, there remains little justification for routine use of invasive reopertations in older adults unless specific criteria exist. \boxed{B}

